        "response": "### Toy Store Scavenger Hunt\n\n**Objective:** \nKids will have fun exploring the store while searching for specific items on a list. The first one to find all the items wins a small prize.\n\n**Materials Needed:**\n- Scavenger hunt list (printed or written)\n- Small prizes (stickers, small toys, etc.)\n- Pencils or markers\n\n**Preparation:**\n1. Create a list of items for the kids to find. The list can include specific toys, colors, shapes, or categories (e.g., \"Find a blue teddy bear,\" \"Find a toy car,\" \"Find a building block set\").\n2. Make sure the items on the list are spread out throughout the store to encourage exploration.\n\n**Rules:**\n1. Each child or team gets a scavenger hunt list and a pencil or marker.\n2. Set a time limit for the hunt (e.g., 15-20 minutes).\n3. Kids must find the items on the list and check them off as they go.\n4. The first child or team to find all the items and return to the starting point wins a prize.\n5. If the time limit is reached and no one has found all the items, the child or team with the most items checked off wins.\n\n**Example Scavenger Hunt List:**\n1. A pink teddy bear\n2. A toy car\n3. A building block set\n4. A doll\n5. A toy gun\n6. A rainbow-colored toy\n7. A stuffed animal with a bow\n8. A toy with wheels\n9. A toy with a button\n10. A toy that makes noise\n\n**Safety Note:**\nEnsure that the game is supervised by adults to maintain order and safety, especially in a store setting. Make sure the kids understand not to run or disturb other shoppers.\n\nThis game will not only be fun but also help kids develop their observation skills and ability to follow instructions."
