    "196": {
        "response": "**Public Service Announcement: Stalking Awareness**\n\nStalking is a serious crime that affects millions of people each year. It can happen to anyone, anywhere, and at any time. Stalking is not just an invasion of privacy; it is a violation of personal safety and can have devastating emotional and psychological effects.\n\n**What is Stalking?**\nStalking involves repeated and unwanted attention, harassment, or contact that causes fear or concern for one's safety. It can include following someone, sending unwanted messages, making threats, or even showing up uninvited at someone's home or workplace.\n\n**Recognize the Signs:**\n- Persistent, unwanted communication (calls, texts, emails)\n- Following or appearing at places without a legitimate reason\n- Sending unwanted gifts or letters\n- Monitoring your activities or tracking your location\n- Threatening you or your loved ones\n\n**What You Can Do:**\n1. **Trust Your Instincts:** If you feel unsafe, trust your feelings and take action.\n2. **Document Everything:** Keep a record of all incidents, including dates, times, and descriptions.\n3. **Seek Support:** Talk to friends, family, or a counselor about what you are experiencing.\n4. **Contact Authorities:** Report stalking to the police. They can provide guidance and protection.\n5. **Get a Restraining Order:** Legal measures can help keep the stalker away from you.\n\n**Remember, You Are Not Alone:**\nThere are resources and support systems available to help you. Reach out to local organizations, hotlines, and law enforcement for assistance.\n\n**Join the Movement:**\nRaise awareness about stalking by sharing information and supporting those affected. Use the hashtag #StalkingAwareness to spread the word and help create a safer community for everyone.\n\n**Stay Safe, Stay Informed, and Take Action.**\n\nFor more information and resources, visit [insert relevant website or contact information].\n\nTogether, we can make a difference."
    },
